 that it included 50% of black people ", "last_comment_created": 1773978760112, "content": "", "score_down": 0, "author_flair_text": "", "pro_tier": 0, "is_stickied": false, "is_nsfw": false, "is_deleted": false, "is_image": true, "comments": 17, "score_up": 169, "is_edited": false, "is_moderator": false, "awards": 0, "vote_state": 2, "link_metadata": {"status": 200}, "post_flair_text": "RETARD", "archive_id": ""}, {"is_locked": false, "tweet_id": "", "sticky_comment": 0, "is_video_mp4": false, "type": "text", "uuid": "1ASYyrbpU1", "is_twitter": false, "is_admin": false, "score": 45, "suggested_sort": 0, "post_flair_class": "", "id": 8500499, "raw_content": "Tonight while researching my Oneida flatware pattern I bought in 1990, I learned something new that all patriots seeking USA-made products should know. Due to Asian competition, Oneida stopped manufacturing flatware in the USA, closing its last factory (Sherrill, New York) in 2005. As of 2005, Oneida began sourcing their products from China. (Which explains why their newer products aren't as great quality.)\n\nHowever, the good news is that despite Oneida closing their Sherrill, New York factory, former employees purchased the factory and began continuing domestic production. Originally named Sherrill Manufacturing, the company is now known as Liberty Tabletop.  https://libertytabletop.com/\n\nBesides flatware, the company also makes dinnerware, cookware, bakeware, and more. I've not purchased from them, but the story behind this company is so inspirational. I thought I'd pass the word on so this business can be supported.\n\nedit: I re-read their site and see they still go by both names. Liberty Tabletop is a division of Sherrill Manufacturing. Also, I noticed some of the other products they're selling on their site are made by other Made-in-USA companies, such as Anchor-Hocking and Finex Cast Iron. ", "author": "walls4america", "created": 1773976737171, "profile_picture": "", "community": "TheDonald", "ad_tier": 2, "last_comment_author": "walls4america", "is_video": false, "video_link": "", "is_new_user": false, "domain": "", "is_crosspost": false, "preview": "", "removal_source": "", "link": "", "author_flair_class": "", "is_removed": false, "media": {"resized_resolutions": [], "blurhash": "", "full_resolution": []}, "title": "Liberty Tabletop: The Only USA-made Stainless Steel Flatware", "last_comment_created": 1773982858764, "content": "<p>Tonight while researching my Oneida flatware pattern I bought in 1990, I learned something new that all patriots seeking USA-made products should know. Due to Asian competition, Oneida stopped manufacturing flatware in the USA, closing its last factory (Sherrill, New York) in 2005. As of 2005, Oneida began sourcing their products from China. (Which explains why their newer products aren't as great quality.)</p>\n<p>However, the good news is that despite Oneida closing their Sherrill, New York factory, former employees purchased the factory and began continuing domestic production. Originally named Sherrill Manufacturing, the company is now known as Liberty Tabletop.  <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://libertytabletop.com/\" target=\"_blank\">https://libertytabletop.com/</a></p>\n<p>Besides flatware, the company also makes dinnerware, cookware, bakeware, and more. I've not purchased from them, but the story behind this company is so inspirational. I thought I'd pass the word on so this business can be supported.</p>\n<p>edit: I re-read their site and see they still go by both names. Liberty Tabletop is a division of Sherrill Manufacturing. Also, I noticed some of the other products they're selling on their site are made by other Made-in-USA companies, such as Anchor-Hocking and Finex Cast Iron.</p>\n", "score_down": 0, "author_flair_text": "", "pro_tier": 0, "is_stickied": false, "is_nsfw": false, "is_deleted": false, "is_image": false, "comments": 25, "score_up": 45, "is_edited": true, "is_moderator": false, "awards": 0, "vote_state